Local Storage vs Session Storage

Both are browser storage mechanisms and both can be viewed and modified by the user, so neither should be trusted for security-sensitive data.

Feature   	                         Local Storage	             Session Storage
Persistence	                         Survives browser restart	 Cleared when tab/window closes
Shared between tabs             	 ✅ Yes (same origin)	   ❌ No (per tab)
Capacity	                         ~5-10 MB	                ~5-10 MB
Accessible by JavaScript	         ✅ Yes                     ✅ Yes
Sent automatically to server	     ❌ No                      ❌ No
User can modify	                     ✅ Yes                     ✅ Yes
Local Storage

Data remains until explicitly removed.

localStorage.setItem("theme", "dark");

Even after:

Refreshing page
Closing browser
Restarting computer

The value still exists.

Read it:

localStorage.getItem("theme");

Remove it:

localStorage.removeItem("theme");
Good use cases

✅ Theme preference

✅ Language selection

✅ UI settings

✅ Cached non-sensitive data

Bad use cases

❌ User role

❌ Wallet balance

❌ Premium status

❌ Admin permissions

❌ Authentication tokens (in most modern apps)

Session Storage

Data exists only for the current browser tab.

sessionStorage.setItem("step", "2");

Close the tab:

Data is gone.

Open a new tab:

Data is not shared.
Good use cases

✅ Multi-step forms

✅ Temporary wizard state

✅ Checkout progress

✅ One-tab temporary data

Example
Local Storage

Tab 1:

localStorage.setItem("user", "Sagar");

Tab 2:

localStorage.getItem("user");

Output:

Sagar

Shared across tabs.

Session Storage

Tab 1:

sessionStorage.setItem("user", "Sagar");

Tab 2:

sessionStorage.getItem("user");

Output:

null

Not shared.

In a Next.js App

Typical usage:

Local Storage
localStorage.setItem("theme", "dark");
localStorage.setItem("cart", JSON.stringify(cart));
Session Storage
sessionStorage.setItem("currentStep", "3");

Useful for onboarding flows or forms.

What do modern apps use?

Examples:

YouTube → Local storage for preferences and caching.
Spotify → Local storage for UI preferences and cached data.
Amazon → Local storage for some client-side state.
Modern auth systems (Next.js + Supabase, Clerk, Auth.js) typically use secure cookies, often HttpOnly, for sessions rather than local storage.
For your projects

For your Next.js + Supabase apps:

Store in Local Storage

Theme
Sidebar state
Last selected city
Search filters
Draft form data

Store on the Server / Database

User role
Wallet balance
Credits
Referral earnings
Premium access
Subscription status
Admin permissions

Store in HttpOnly Cookies

Authentication session
Refresh tokens
Login state

That's the architecture commonly used in production applications because anything in Local Storage or Session Storage should be treated as user-editable.